pan=\"2\" |2021\n!#GSSS41{{Dagger}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!#GSSS42{{Dagger}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n\n\n'''Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Film\n!Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[PoraMon|Bioscope Borsho - Shera Awards]] \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[PoraMon]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Nominated\n|-\n|Best Couple with ([[Mahiya Mahi]]) \n|-\n|2016\n|[[Babisas Award|Babisas Award for Featured Actor Male]]\n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film actor]] \n|_\n|Nominated\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|AJFB Star Awards]] \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]] \n|_\n|Nominated \n|-\n|[[43rd Bangladesh National Film Awards]]\n|[[Symon Sadik|Best Film Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]\n|Won\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Symon Sadik|AJFB Star Awards]]  \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]]\n|Nominated \n|}\n\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n# [[PoraMon|\"\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 \u09aa\u09cb\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09ae\u09a8 (\u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09e9) \u099c\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09b0 \u09b9\u09cb\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09a8 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09c1 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4 \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09c7 \u099c\u09a8\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a4\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09ad \u0995\u09b0\u09c7\"]]\n#[[PoraMon|\u09a6\u09b0\u09cd\u09b6\u0995 \u09ad\u09cb\u099f\u09c7 \"\u09ac\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09cb\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09cb\u09aa \u09ac\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09b8\u09c7\u09b0\u09be\" \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09e9 \u09b9\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995]] \n#\"Symon Sadik Won, [[Babisas Award]] for Featured Actor Male in (2016)\".\n#[[Bobby (actress)|\"\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09b0 \u099c\u09c1\u099f\u09bf, \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09aa\u09cd\u09a8 \u099b\u09cb\u0981\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u0985\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0995\u09b6\u09a8 \u099c\u09c7\u09b8\u09ae\u09bf\u09a8\"]]\n#[[Moushumi Hamid|\"\u09ae\u09cc\u09b8\u09c1\u09ae\u09c0 \u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09bf\u09a6 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \"Black Money\" \u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2\"]] \n#[[Airin Sultana|\"Horror and Comedy movie \"Mayabiny\" in (2017) Airin sultana with Symon Sadik\"]]\n#[[Misty Jannat|\"\"\u09ae\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09bf \u099c\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be\u09a4 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 (\u09a4\u09c1\u0987 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09c7\"\"]]\n#[[Jannat (2018 film)|\"\u0986\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cb \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09ae\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09b0 \u099c\u09c1\u099f\u09bf, \u09ae\u09cb\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09be\u09ab\u09bf\u099c\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09b9\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4 (\u099c\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be\u09a4 \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ee) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09c7\"]]\n#[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor|\"\"\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u099a\u09b2\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0 \u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 \"\"]]\n#[[Adhora Khan|\"\"\u0985\u09a7\u09b0\u09be \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 (\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09b2) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be \u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2 \"\"]] \n#\"\u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u0985\u09a7\u09b0\u09be\u09b0 '\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09b2\". ''Janakantha'' (in Bengali). 27 October 2018. Retrieved 28 July 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|6084492}}\n{{Bangladesh National Film Award Best Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control|Awards and Nominate=}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadik, Symon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kishoreganj District]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male film actors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Film Awards (Bangladesh)]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sohail ariyan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symon_Sadik"}
{"title_page": "Nate Dogg", "text_new": "{{Short description|American rapper and actor from California}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Nate Dogg\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Nate dogg rapradar.jpg\n| caption = Hale at Recording Academy Honors in Hollywood on June 8, 2006\n| birth_name = Nathaniel Dwayne Hale\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1969|08|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| origin = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2011|3|15|1969|08|19}}\n| death_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[West Coast hip hop]]\n* [[gangsta rap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[G-funk]]\n* [[hip hop soul]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* actor\n}}\n| years_active = 1990\u20132008\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Death Row Records|Death Row]]\n* [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n* [[Doggystyle Records|Doggystyle]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[213 (group)|213]]\n* [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]]\n* [[50 Cent]]\n* [[Dr. Dre]]\n* [[Eminem]]\n* [[Fabolous]]\n* [[MC Ren]]\n* [[Obie Trice]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[Shade Sheist]]\n* [[Tha Dogg Pound]]\n* [[Thug Life]]\n* [[Warren G]]\n* [[Westside Connection]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Nathaniel Dwayne Hale''' (August 19, 1969 \u2013 March 15, 2011), known professionally as '''Nate Dogg''', was an American rapper, singer, songwriter, and actor. Hale began his career as a member of the [[Long Beach, California]] rap trio [[213 (group)|213]], alongside his longtime friend [[Warren G]] and cousin [[Snoop Dogg]]. He eventually pursued a solo career, and released three solo albums, ''[[G-Funk Classics, Vol. 1 & 2]]'' in 1998, ''[[Music & Me (Nate Dogg album)|Music & Me]]'' in 2001, and ''[[Nate Dogg (album)|Nate Dogg]]'' as a bootlegged album in 2003 and on CD in 2014.\n\nHe was known for his deep, low-pitched singing voice, and for performing [[Hook (music)|hooks]], frequently collaborating with other artists such as [[Dr. Dre]], [[Eminem]], [[Warren G]], [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Westside Connection]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[50 Cent]], [[Ludacris]], [[Xzibit]], and [[Shade Sheist]] on many hit releases.<ref>{{cite news|first=Garth|last=Cartwright|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/mar/16/nate-dogg-obituary|title=Nate Dogg obituary|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=March 16, 2011|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Nate Dogg is regarded as one of the pioneers of [[G-funk]] and [[West Coast hip hop]].\n\nHale died in 2011 due to complications from multiple strokes.<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\">{{cite magazine|first=Matthew|last=Perpetua|title=Rapper and Singer Nate Dogg Dead at 41|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/rapper-and-singer-nate-dogg-dead-at-41-20110316|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|location=New York City|date=March 15, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNathaniel Dwayne Hale was born in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]] on August 19, 1969.<ref>{{Cite news|first1=Gerrick D.|last1=Kennedy|first2=Valerie J.|last2=Nelson|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/17/local/la-me-nate-dogg-20110317|title=Nate Dogg dies at 41; West Coast rapper created the blend of singing-rapping known as G-funk|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=June 21, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He moved to [[Long Beach, California]] when he was 14 following his parents' divorce. He was friends [[Warren G]], [[RBX]] and [[Dr. Dre]] and cousin of [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Daz Dillinger]], [[Butch Cassidy (singer)|Butch Cassidy]], and Lil' \u00bd Dead. He began singing as a child in the New Hope Baptist Church in Long Beach and Life Line Baptist Church in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]] where his father Daniel Lee Hale pastored and his mother Ruth Holmes was leading the choir.\n\n== Military career ==\nAt the age of 17, Hale dropped out of high school, left home, and 30 days later enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]].<ref name=\"marine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.usmc.net/famous_us_marines/ |title=Joining the Ranks of Famous Marines |publisher=USMC.net |accessdate=December 26, 2009 }}</ref> Hale was stationed in [[Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa, Japan]] at Camp Schwab as part of the Material Readiness Battalion of the 3rd Force Service Support Group, which served as the supplier of ammunition  to the majority of the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]]. He served three years as an ammunition specialist, and was [[military discharge|discharged]] in 1989. Hale said he joined the military because he \"wanted to see if he was a man\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Arnold|url=https://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.1899/title.souljas-story-10-hip-hop-artists-who-served-their-country|title=Soulja's Story: 10 Hip Hop Artists Who Served Their Country|website=hiphopdx.com|location=Portland, Oregon|date=May 28, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career with 213===\nIn 1990,<ref name=\"About\"/> Nate Dogg, [[Snoop Dogg]],<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200247/biography|pure_url=yes}} Nate Dogg Biography], [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 2, 2006.</ref> and [[Warren G]], formed a rap trio called [[213 (group)|213]].<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://www.warreng.com/about|title=Warren G|accessdate=2019-09-28}}</ref> They recorded their first demo in the back of the famed V.I.P. record store in Long Beach. The demo was later heard by [[Dr. Dre]] at a bachelor party.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ness |first1=Jimmy |title=Where Rhythm is Life & Life Is Rhythm: An Interview with Warren G |url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2015/08/25/warren-g-interview/ |website=Passion of the Weiss |accessdate=23 July 2018 |date=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nNate Dogg made his debut on ''[[The Chronic]]''. Singing in what later became his trademark style, he was well received by fans and critics alike, and would go on to sign with [[Death Row Records]] in 1993. Nate Dogg was additionally featured on [[Snoop Dogg]]'s 1993 album ''[[Doggystyle]]'' such as the track \"Ain't No Fun (If the Homies Can't Have None)\". Nate Dogg was also featured on Mista Grimm's \"Indosmoke\" with Warren G. Then in 1994 he produced his first hit single \"[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]\" with [[Warren G]]. Nate Dogg was also featured in many [[2Pac]] releases, including his collaboration record ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]''. Then in 1998 after a tumultuous time at Death Row Records he released another album. The double album was titled ''G-Funk Classics Vol. 1 & 2'' and was followed up in late 2001 with ''Music & Me'' on [[Elektra Records]]. ''Music & Me'' peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' hip-hop charts in 2001.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200247/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}} Nate- Charts and Awards], [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 2, 2006</ref> After a number of delays and an original release date of April 2004, his [[Nate Dogg (album)|self-titled album]] was released under the ''Affiliated Entertainment Group'' on June 3, 2008.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Television appearances===\nIn 2002, Nate Dogg appeared on a celebrity episode of ''[[The Weakest Link (American game show)|The Weakest Link]]'',  making it to the last three players before being eliminated by Xzibit and [[Young MC]].<ref name=\"mtvweakestlink\">{{cite web|first=Shaheem|last=Reid|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452885/rappers-face-off-on-weakest-link.jhtml|title=Xzibit, B-Real, DJ Quik Face Off On Hip-Hop 'Weakest Link'|website=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|location=New York City|date=March 13, 2002|accessdate=February 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Collaborations with other artists===\nNate Dogg was well known for his collaborations with other artists, where he would usually perform the [[Refrain|hook]]. As a featured artist, Nate Dogg charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] sixteen times, and reached number one on the chart in 2003, when he was featured on [[50 Cent]]'s \"[[21 Questions]]\". According to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', along with \"21 Questions\", Nate Dogg's most successful collaborations include [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]]'s \"[[All Eyez on Me|All Bout U]]\", [[Dr. Dre]]'s \"[[The Next Episode]]\", [[Westside Connection]]'s \"[[Gangsta Nation]]\", [[Mos Def]]'s \"Oh No\", [[Fabolous]]' \"[[Can't Deny It]]\", [[Ludacris]]' \"[[Area Codes (song)|Area Codes]]\", [[Kurupt]]'s \"Behind The Walls\", [[Mark Ronson]]'s \"Ooh Wee\", [[Houston (singer)|Houston]]'s \"[[I Like That (Houston song)|I Like That]]\", [[Eminem]]'s \"[['Till I Collapse]]\", \"Never Enough\", and \"[[Shake That]]\", and [[Mobb Deep]]'s \"[[Have a Party]]\".<ref name=\"Top Collaborations\">{{cite web|last=Perpetua|first=Matthew|title=Nate Dogg's Best Guest Appearances|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/nate-doggs-best-guest-appearances-20110316/warren-g-featuring-nate-dogg-regulate-1994-0119022|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legal troubles ==\nIn the early 1990s, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with two separate robberies: the Check Changers robbery in 1991 and the robbery of a [[San Pedro, Los Angeles|San Pedro]] [[Taco Bell]] in 1994.<ref name=\"cases\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8FF7EB702DFB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=L.B. Rapper Nate Dogg Out On Bail In Robbery Charge |work=Press-Telegram |date=December 14, 1994 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE90E01DF7AB5B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nate Dogg Acquitted Of '91 Robbery Charges |work=Press-Telegram |date=July 22, 1996 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He faced a maximum of nearly eleven years in prison,<ref name=\"robbery\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8FFE3724BC63&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=L.B. Rapper Suspected of Robbery |work=Press-Telegram |date=December 19, 1994 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 15, 2018 }}</ref> but was subsequently [[Acquittal|acquitted]] of both charges.<ref name=\"latimes\"/><ref name=\"robbery\"/>\n\nIn 1996, Nate Dogg was convicted of a drug-related offense in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]].<ref name=\"charges\">{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fqFIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cQsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2583,12574 |title=Firearm charges dog another rapper |work=The Post and Courier |date=March 16, 2001 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 17, 2000, Nate Dogg was arrested for allegedly kidnapping and assaulting his former girlfriend and setting fire to her mother's car in [[Lakewood, California|Lakewood]]. He was then arrested by a [[SWAT]] team at his home in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]]. He was accused of kidnapping, domestic violence, making terrorist threats and arson.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TE0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=a8kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2870,2389837 |title=Nate Dogg arrested |agency=Associated Press   |date=June 16, 2000 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He spent a night in the [[Twin Towers Correctional Facility]] in Los Angeles before he was released on a $1&nbsp;million bail posted by Dr. Dre.<ref name=\"bail\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8B414DD615CD&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rapper Nate Dogg Charged on 5 Counts |work=Press-Telegram |date=July 15, 2000 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> These charges were later dismissed, but he faced jail time for a new charge, illegal possession of a firearm by a felon. An unmarked firearm was found in his home during the June 17 arrest.<ref name=\"charges\"/> He pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to the misdemeanor charge, and was sentenced to three years of [[probation]] and ordered to pay a $1,000 fine.<ref name=\"probation\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EE15D1E6658A22E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rapper Nate Dogg takes plea bargain |work=Press-Telegram |date=August 22, 2001 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2002, Nate Dogg was arrested when he was stopped by [[Arizona Department of Public Safety]] officers outside of [[Kingman, Arizona]], while traveling on a tour bus. He was charged with firearms-related and drug-related offenses after two pistols and four ounces of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] were found. Nate Dogg was booked into Mohave County Jail and subsequently released on a $3,500 bond.<ref name=\"mohave\">{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Seckler |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LNpPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D1MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4186,1301415 |title=Rap singer released on bond after drug, gun arrest locally |work=[[Kingman Daily Miner]] |date=April 16, 2002 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> Weapon charges against him were dropped as an exchange for a plea of guilty on a drug possession charge. Nate Dogg was subsequently sentenced to probation and community service. He was also ordered to attend drug counseling sessions in May 2002.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web |first=Noah |last=Callahan-Bever |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1454560/nate-dogg-sentenced-drug-possession.jhtml |title=Nate Dogg Sentenced For Drug Possession |publisher=MTV News |date=May 28, 2002 |accessdate=March 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with misdemeanor aggravated trespassing, telephone harassment, battery assault, dissuading a witness from reporting a crime and violation of a [[restraining order]]. In March 20, 2008, Nate Dogg pleaded guilty to trespassing and battery and was ordered to complete a domestic violence treatment program, three years of probation, and was stripped of gun ownership rights for the next ten years.<ref name=\"hiphopdx\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.6636/title.nate-dogg-pleads-guilty-in-domestic-violence-charge |title=Nate Dogg Pleads Guilty In Domestic Violence Charge |work=HipHopDX |date=March 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2008, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with two felony counts of making criminal threats after allegedly sending [[death threat|threatening]] emails to his estranged wife,<ref name=\"dropped\">{{cite news |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705297775/Stalking-charge-dropped-against-Nate-Dogg.html |title=Stalking charge dropped against Nate Dogg |agency=Associated Press   |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> and one count of [[stalking]] after allegedly chasing her by car on [[Interstate 405 (California)|Interstate 405]] in the previous month.<ref name=\"dui\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=121FD15FC57C6B40&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nate Dogg Pleads Not Guilty to Making Threats, Stalking Estranged Wife |work=Long Beach Press-Telegram |date=July 17, 2008 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He initially pleaded not guilty to these charges,<ref name=\"dui\"/> which were eventually dropped in April 2009, because the alleged victim did not contact prosecutors in the case.<ref name=\"dropped\"/>\n\nAdditionally, Nate Dogg had a conviction of [[Drug\u2013impaired driving|driving under the influence of drugs]].<ref name=\"dui\"/>\n\n==Health issues and death==\n[[File:Graffiti upami\u0119tniaj\u0105ce Nate Dogga na uj\u015bciu wody oligoce\u0144skiej przy skrzy\u017cowaniu al. Solidarno\u015bci i ul. \u017belaznej w Warszawie..jpg|thumb|Graffiti on Solidarno\u015bci Avenue in [[Warsaw]], April 2012]]\nOn December 19, 2007, Hale suffered a [[stroke]], according to a coordinator from his recently formed [[Gospel music|gospel choir]], Innate Praise.<ref name=\"mtvstroke\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1579019/hannah-montana-contest-winner-apologizes-fake-essay.jhtml|title=Hannah Montana Contest Winner Apologizes For Fake Essay; Plus 'American Idol,' C-Murder, R.E.M., Birdman & More, In For The Record|date=January 4, 2008|accessdate=February 17, 2011|publisher=MTV}}</ref> He was released from the hospital one week later and admitted to a [[Physical medicine and rehabilitation|medical rehabilitation]] facility. Despite the stroke having paralyzed the [[Hemiparesis|left side]] of his body, his doctors believed there would be a full recovery and his voice would not be affected. However, on September 12, 2008, Hale suffered a second stroke.<ref name=MTV>Jayson Rodriguez (January 18, 2008). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1579891/20080118/nate_dogg.jhtml Nate Dogg Paralyzed After Stroke; Manager Slams Coverage Of 911 Call], MTV. Retrieved January 19, 2008.</ref> He died on March 15, 2011, in [[Long Beach, California]] at age 41,<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\"/> and was interred at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in Long Beach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66995284|title=Nathaniel Dwayne \"Nate Dogg\" Hale (1969 - 2011) - Find A Grave Memorial|publisher=}}</ref> Hale's attorney, [[Mark Geragos]], confirmed the cause of death as complications from multiple strokes.<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Hale's son, Nathaniel Jr., released his own album titled ''Son of a G'', under the name Lil Nate Dogg.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nate Dogg\u2019s son Lil Nate Dogg \"Son Of A G\" album out now|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/3618629}}</ref> His other son, Naijiel, attended the [[University of Arizona]] to play football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hip-Hop Singer Nate Dogg\u2019s Son, Naijiel Hale, Commits to Arizona for Football (Video)|url=https://nesn.com/2013/07/hip-hop-singer-nate-doggs-son-naijiel-hale-commits-to-arizona-for-football-video/|website=NESN.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017|date=July 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Nate Dogg discography}}\n\n===Solo albums===\n*''[[G-Funk Classics, Vol. 1 & 2]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Music & Me (Nate Dogg album)|Music & Me]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Nate Dogg (album)|Nate Dogg]]'' (2003)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n*''[[The Hard Way (213 album)|The Hard Way]]'' <small>(with 213)</small> (2004)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Doggy Fizzle Televizzle]]'' (2002\u20132003)\n* ''[[Head of State (2003 film)|Head of State]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Boondocks (TV series)|The Boondocks]]'' (2008)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nDuring his career, Nate Dogg was nominated for four [[Grammy Awards]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:\"\n! Category\n! Genre\n! Song\n! Year\n! Result\n|-\n| Best Rap/Sung Collaboration {{small|(with [[Eminem]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[Shake That]]\"\n| 2007\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap/Sung Collaboration {{small|(with [[Ludacris]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"Area Codes\"\n| 2002\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group {{small|(uncredited with [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Snoop Dogg]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[The Next Episode]]\"\n| 2001\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group {{small|(with [[Warren G]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]\"\n| 1995\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best R&B Album {{small|(with [[Anderson .Paak]]) (as featuring artist)}}\n| R&B\n| \"[[Ventura (Anderson Paak album)|What Can We Do? (feat. Nate Dogg)]]\"\n| 2020\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{MTV artist|nate-dogg}}\n* {{IMDb name|0230489}}\n* {{Find a Grave|66995284}}\n\n{{Nate Dogg}}\n{{213}}\n{{Tha Dogg Pound}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dogg, Nate}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Death Row Records artists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cerebrovascular disease]]\n[[Category:G-funk artists]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Clarksdale, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:213 (group) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American rapper and actor from California}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Nate Dogg\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Nate dogg rapradar.jpg\n| caption = Hale at Recording Academy Honors in Hollywood on June 8, 2006\n| birth_name = Nathaniel Dwayne Hale\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1969|08|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| origin = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2011|3|15|1969|08|19}}\n| death_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[West Coast hip hop]]\n* [[gangsta rap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[G-funk]]\n* [[hip hop soul]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* actor\n}}\n| years_active = 1990\u20132011\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Death Row Records|Death Row]]\n* [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n* [[Doggystyle Records|Doggystyle]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[213 (group)|213]]\n* [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]]\n* [[50 Cent]]\n* [[Dr. Dre]]\n* [[Eminem]]\n* [[Fabolous]]\n* [[MC Ren]]\n* [[Obie Trice]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[Shade Sheist]]\n* [[Tha Dogg Pound]]\n* [[Thug Life]]\n* [[Warren G]]\n* [[Westside Connection]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Nathaniel Dwayne Hale''' (August 19, 1969 \u2013 March 15, 2011), known professionally as '''Nate Dogg''', was an American rapper, singer, songwriter, and actor. Hale began his career as a member of the [[Long Beach, California]] rap trio [[213 (group)|213]], alongside his longtime friend [[Warren G]] and cousin [[Snoop Dogg]]. He eventually pursued a solo career, and released three solo albums, ''[[G-Funk Classics, Vol. 1 & 2]]'' in 1998, ''[[Music & Me (Nate Dogg album)|Music & Me]]'' in 2001, and ''[[Nate Dogg (album)|Nate Dogg]]'' as a bootlegged album in 2003 and on CD in 2014.\n\nHe was known for his deep, low-pitched singing voice, and for performing [[Hook (music)|hooks]], frequently collaborating with other artists such as [[Dr. Dre]], [[Eminem]], [[Warren G]], [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Westside Connection]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[50 Cent]], [[Ludacris]], [[Xzibit]], and [[Shade Sheist]] on many hit releases.<ref>{{cite news|first=Garth|last=Cartwright|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/mar/16/nate-dogg-obituary|title=Nate Dogg obituary|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=March 16, 2011|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Nate Dogg is regarded as one of the pioneers of [[G-funk]] and [[West Coast hip hop]].\n\nHale died in 2011 due to complications from multiple strokes.<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\">{{cite magazine|first=Matthew|last=Perpetua|title=Rapper and Singer Nate Dogg Dead at 41|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/rapper-and-singer-nate-dogg-dead-at-41-20110316|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|location=New York City|date=March 15, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNathaniel Dwayne Hale was born in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]] on August 19, 1969.<ref>{{Cite news|first1=Gerrick D.|last1=Kennedy|first2=Valerie J.|last2=Nelson|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/17/local/la-me-nate-dogg-20110317|title=Nate Dogg dies at 41; West Coast rapper created the blend of singing-rapping known as G-funk|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=June 21, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He moved to [[Long Beach, California]] when he was 14 following his parents' divorce. He was friends [[Warren G]], [[RBX]] and [[Dr. Dre]] and cousin of [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Daz Dillinger]], [[Butch Cassidy (singer)|Butch Cassidy]], and Lil' \u00bd Dead. He began singing as a child in the New Hope Baptist Church in Long Beach and Life Line Baptist Church in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]] where his father Daniel Lee Hale pastored and his mother Ruth Holmes was leading the choir.\n\n== Military career ==\nAt the age of 17, Hale dropped out of high school, left home, and 30 days later enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]].<ref name=\"marine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.usmc.net/famous_us_marines/ |title=Joining the Ranks of Famous Marines |publisher=USMC.net |accessdate=December 26, 2009 }}</ref> Hale was stationed in [[Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa, Japan]] at Camp Schwab as part of the Material Readiness Battalion of the 3rd Force Service Support Group, which served as the supplier of ammunition  to the majority of the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]]. He served three years as an ammunition specialist, and was [[military discharge|discharged]] in 1989. Hale said he joined the military because he \"wanted to see if he was a man\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Arnold|url=https://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.1899/title.souljas-story-10-hip-hop-artists-who-served-their-country|title=Soulja's Story: 10 Hip Hop Artists Who Served Their Country|website=hiphopdx.com|location=Portland, Oregon|date=May 28, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career with 213===\nIn 1990,<ref name=\"About\"/> Nate Dogg, [[Snoop Dogg]],<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200247/biography|pure_url=yes}} Nate Dogg Biography], [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 2, 2006.</ref> and [[Warren G]], formed a rap trio called [[213 (group)|213]].<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://www.warreng.com/about|title=Warren G|accessdate=2019-09-28}}</ref> They recorded their first demo in the back of the famed V.I.P. record store in Long Beach. The demo was later heard by [[Dr. Dre]] at a bachelor party.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ness |first1=Jimmy |title=Where Rhythm is Life & Life Is Rhythm: An Interview with Warren G |url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2015/08/25/warren-g-interview/ |website=Passion of the Weiss |accessdate=23 July 2018 |date=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nNate Dogg made his debut on ''[[The Chronic]]''. Singing in what later became his trademark style, he was well received by fans and critics alike, and would go on to sign with [[Death Row Records]] in 1993. Nate Dogg was additionally featured on [[Snoop Dogg]]'s 1993 album ''[[Doggystyle]]'' such as the track \"Ain't No Fun (If the Homies Can't Have None)\". Nate Dogg was also featured on Mista Grimm's \"Indosmoke\" with Warren G. Then in 1994 he produced his first hit single \"[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]\" with [[Warren G]]. Nate Dogg was also featured in many [[2Pac]] releases, including his collaboration record ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]''. Then in 1998 after a tumultuous time at Death Row Records he released another album. The double album was titled ''G-Funk Classics Vol. 1 & 2'' and was followed up in late 2001 with ''Music & Me'' on [[Elektra Records]]. ''Music & Me'' peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' hip-hop charts in 2001.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200247/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}} Nate- Charts and Awards], [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 2, 2006</ref> After a number of delays and an original release date of April 2004, his [[Nate Dogg (album)|self-titled album]] was released under the ''Affiliated Entertainment Group'' on June 3, 2008.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Television appearances===\nIn 2002, Nate Dogg appeared on a celebrity episode of ''[[The Weakest Link (American game show)|The Weakest Link]]'',  making it to the last three players before being eliminated by Xzibit and [[Young MC]].<ref name=\"mtvweakestlink\">{{cite web|first=Shaheem|last=Reid|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452885/rappers-face-off-on-weakest-link.jhtml|title=Xzibit, B-Real, DJ Quik Face Off On Hip-Hop 'Weakest Link'|website=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|location=New York City|date=March 13, 2002|accessdate=February 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Collaborations with other artists===\nNate Dogg was well known for his collaborations with other artists, where he would usually perform the [[Refrain|hook]]. As a featured artist, Nate Dogg charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] sixteen times, and reached number one on the chart in 2003, when he was featured on [[50 Cent]]'s \"[[21 Questions]]\". According to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', along with \"21 Questions\", Nate Dogg's most successful collaborations include [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]]'s \"[[All Eyez on Me|All Bout U]]\", [[Dr. Dre]]'s \"[[The Next Episode]]\", [[Westside Connection]]'s \"[[Gangsta Nation]]\", [[Mos Def]]'s \"Oh No\", [[Fabolous]]' \"[[Can't Deny It]]\", [[Ludacris]]' \"[[Area Codes (song)|Area Codes]]\", [[Kurupt]]'s \"Behind The Walls\", [[Mark Ronson]]'s \"Ooh Wee\", [[Houston (singer)|Houston]]'s \"[[I Like That (Houston song)|I Like That]]\", [[Eminem]]'s \"[['Till I Collapse]]\", \"Never Enough\", and \"[[Shake That]]\", and [[Mobb Deep]]'s \"[[Have a Party]]\".<ref name=\"Top Collaborations\">{{cite web|last=Perpetua|first=Matthew|title=Nate Dogg's Best Guest Appearances|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/nate-doggs-best-guest-appearances-20110316/warren-g-featuring-nate-dogg-regulate-1994-0119022|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legal troubles ==\nIn the early 1990s, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with two separate robberies: the Check Changers robbery in 1991 and the robbery of a [[San Pedro, Los Angeles|San Pedro]] [[Taco Bell]] in 1994.<ref name=\"cases\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8FF7EB702DFB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=L.B. Rapper Nate Dogg Out On Bail In Robbery Charge |work=Press-Telegram |date=December 14, 1994 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE90E01DF7AB5B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nate Dogg Acquitted Of '91 Robbery Charges |work=Press-Telegram |date=July 22, 1996 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He faced a maximum of nearly eleven years in prison,<ref name=\"robbery\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8FFE3724BC63&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=L.B. Rapper Suspected of Robbery |work=Press-Telegram |date=December 19, 1994 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 15, 2018 }}</ref> but was subsequently [[Acquittal|acquitted]] of both charges.<ref name=\"latimes\"/><ref name=\"robbery\"/>\n\nIn 1996, Nate Dogg was convicted of a drug-related offense in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]].<ref name=\"charges\">{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fqFIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cQsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2583,12574 |title=Firearm charges dog another rapper |work=The Post and Courier |date=March 16, 2001 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 17, 2000, Nate Dogg was arrested for allegedly kidnapping and assaulting his former girlfriend and setting fire to her mother's car in [[Lakewood, California|Lakewood]]. He was then arrested by a [[SWAT]] team at his home in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]]. He was accused of kidnapping, domestic violence, making terrorist threats and arson.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TE0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=a8kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2870,2389837 |title=Nate Dogg arrested |agency=Associated Press   |date=June 16, 2000 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He spent a night in the [[Twin Towers Correctional Facility]] in Los Angeles before he was released on a $1&nbsp;million bail posted by Dr. Dre.<ref name=\"bail\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8B414DD615CD&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rapper Nate Dogg Charged on 5 Counts |work=Press-Telegram |date=July 15, 2000 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> These charges were later dismissed, but he faced jail time for a new charge, illegal possession of a firearm by a felon. An unmarked firearm was found in his home during the June 17 arrest.<ref name=\"charges\"/> He pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to the misdemeanor charge, and was sentenced to three years of [[probation]] and ordered to pay a $1,000 fine.<ref name=\"probation\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EE15D1E6658A22E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rapper Nate Dogg takes plea bargain |work=Press-Telegram |date=August 22, 2001 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2002, Nate Dogg was arrested when he was stopped by [[Arizona Department of Public Safety]] officers outside of [[Kingman, Arizona]], while traveling on a tour bus. He was charged with firearms-related and drug-related offenses after two pistols and four ounces of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] were found. Nate Dogg was booked into Mohave County Jail and subsequently released on a $3,500 bond.<ref name=\"mohave\">{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Seckler |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LNpPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D1MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4186,1301415 |title=Rap singer released on bond after drug, gun arrest locally |work=[[Kingman Daily Miner]] |date=April 16, 2002 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> Weapon charges against him were dropped as an exchange for a plea of guilty on a drug possession charge. Nate Dogg was subsequently sentenced to probation and community service. He was also ordered to attend drug counseling sessions in May 2002.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web |first=Noah |last=Callahan-Bever |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1454560/nate-dogg-sentenced-drug-possession.jhtml |title=Nate Dogg Sentenced For Drug Possession |publisher=MTV News |date=May 28, 2002 |accessdate=March 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with misdemeanor aggravated trespassing, telephone harassment, battery assault, dissuading a witness from reporting a crime and violation of a [[restraining order]]. In March 20, 2008, Nate Dogg pleaded guilty to trespassing and battery and was ordered to complete a domestic violence treatment program, three years of probation, and was stripped of gun ownership rights for the next ten years.<ref name=\"hiphopdx\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.6636/title.nate-dogg-pleads-guilty-in-domestic-violence-charge |title=Nate Dogg Pleads Guilty In Domestic Violence Charge |work=HipHopDX |date=March 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2008, Nate Dogg was arrested and charged with two felony counts of making criminal threats after allegedly sending [[death threat|threatening]] emails to his estranged wife,<ref name=\"dropped\">{{cite news |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705297775/Stalking-charge-dropped-against-Nate-Dogg.html |title=Stalking charge dropped against Nate Dogg |agency=Associated Press   |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> and one count of [[stalking]] after allegedly chasing her by car on [[Interstate 405 (California)|Interstate 405]] in the previous month.<ref name=\"dui\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=121FD15FC57C6B40&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nate Dogg Pleads Not Guilty to Making Threats, Stalking Estranged Wife |work=Long Beach Press-Telegram |date=July 17, 2008 |format=Fee required |accessdate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> He initially pleaded not guilty to these charges,<ref name=\"dui\"/> which were eventually dropped in April 2009, because the alleged victim did not contact prosecutors in the case.<ref name=\"dropped\"/>\n\nAdditionally, Nate Dogg had a conviction of [[Drug\u2013impaired driving|driving under the influence of drugs]].<ref name=\"dui\"/>\n\n==Health issues and death==\n[[File:Graffiti upami\u0119tniaj\u0105ce Nate Dogga na uj\u015bciu wody oligoce\u0144skiej przy skrzy\u017cowaniu al. Solidarno\u015bci i ul. \u017belaznej w Warszawie..jpg|thumb|Graffiti on Solidarno\u015bci Avenue in [[Warsaw]], April 2012]]\nOn December 19, 2007, Hale suffered a [[stroke]], according to a coordinator from his recently formed [[Gospel music|gospel choir]], Innate Praise.<ref name=\"mtvstroke\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1579019/hannah-montana-contest-winner-apologizes-fake-essay.jhtml|title=Hannah Montana Contest Winner Apologizes For Fake Essay; Plus 'American Idol,' C-Murder, R.E.M., Birdman & More, In For The Record|date=January 4, 2008|accessdate=February 17, 2011|publisher=MTV}}</ref> He was released from the hospital one week later and admitted to a [[Physical medicine and rehabilitation|medical rehabilitation]] facility. Despite the stroke having paralyzed the [[Hemiparesis|left side]] of his body, his doctors believed there would be a full recovery and his voice would not be affected. However, on September 12, 2008, Hale suffered a second stroke.<ref name=MTV>Jayson Rodriguez (January 18, 2008). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1579891/20080118/nate_dogg.jhtml Nate Dogg Paralyzed After Stroke; Manager Slams Coverage Of 911 Call], MTV. Retrieved January 19, 2008.</ref> He died on March 15, 2011, in [[Long Beach, California]] at age 41,<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\"/> and was interred at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in Long Beach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66995284|title=Nathaniel Dwayne \"Nate Dogg\" Hale (1969 - 2011) - Find A Grave Memorial|publisher=}}</ref> Hale's attorney, [[Mark Geragos]], confirmed the cause of death as complications from multiple strokes.<ref name=\"Nate Dogg Died\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Hale's son, Nathaniel Jr., released his own album titled ''Son of a G'', under the name Lil Nate Dogg.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nate Dogg\u2019s son Lil Nate Dogg \"Son Of A G\" album out now|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/3618629}}</ref> His other son, Naijiel, attended the [[University of Arizona]] to play football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hip-Hop Singer Nate Dogg\u2019s Son, Naijiel Hale, Commits to Arizona for Football (Video)|url=https://nesn.com/2013/07/hip-hop-singer-nate-doggs-son-naijiel-hale-commits-to-arizona-for-football-video/|website=NESN.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017|date=July 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Nate Dogg discography}}\n\n===Solo albums===\n*''[[G-Funk Classics, Vol. 1 & 2]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Music & Me (Nate Dogg album)|Music & Me]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Nate Dogg (album)|Nate Dogg]]'' (2003)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n*''[[The Hard Way (213 album)|The Hard Way]]'' <small>(with 213)</small> (2004)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Doggy Fizzle Televizzle]]'' (2002\u20132003)\n* ''[[Head of State (2003 film)|Head of State]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Boondocks (TV series)|The Boondocks]]'' (2008)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nDuring his career, Nate Dogg was nominated for four [[Grammy Awards]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:\"\n! Category\n! Genre\n! Song\n! Year\n! Result\n|-\n| Best Rap/Sung Collaboration {{small|(with [[Eminem]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[Shake That]]\"\n| 2007\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap/Sung Collaboration {{small|(with [[Ludacris]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"Area Codes\"\n| 2002\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group {{small|(uncredited with [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Snoop Dogg]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[The Next Episode]]\"\n| 2001\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group {{small|(with [[Warren G]])}}\n| Rap\n| \"[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]\"\n| 1995\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best R&B Album {{small|(with [[Anderson .Paak]]) (as featuring artist)}}\n| R&B\n| \"[[Ventura (Anderson Paak album)|What Can We Do? (feat. Nate Dogg)]]\"\n| 2020\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{MTV artist|nate-dogg}}\n* {{IMDb name|0230489}}\n* {{Find a Grave|66995284}}\n\n{{Nate Dogg}}\n{{213}}\n{{Tha Dogg Pound}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dogg, Nate}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Death Row Records artists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cerebrovascular disease]]\n[[Category:G-funk artists]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Clarksdale, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:213 (group) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Nonstopmaximum", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nate_Dogg"}
{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a lineal urban neighborhood and pedestrian path in [[Naples, Italy]].  It descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with adjacent lower neighborhoods before terminating in downtown Naples, in its [[Chiaia]] quarter.\n\nFormerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally an ancient, natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As the path was trafficked, inhabited and developed, it was improved to a narrow series of connected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width &mdash; and framed by buildings, churches,and small businesses.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\nThe Petraio is accessible only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and broad views of the city. It is one of roughly more than 200 neighborhood stairs, inclined walks and ramps in Naples.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==Access and sections==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nProminent sub-sections include:\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of Genoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla, which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli.\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a lineal urban neighborhood and pedestrian path in [[Naples, Italy]].  It descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with adjacent lower neighborhoods before terminating in downtown Naples, in its [[Chiaia]] quarter.\n\nFormerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally an ancient, natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As the path was trafficked, inhabited and developed, it was improved to a narrow series of connected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width &mdash; and framed by buildings, churches,and small businesses.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\nThe Petraio is accessible only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and broad views of the city.\n\n==Access and sections==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nThe Petraio comprises a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\nProminent sub-sections include:\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of Genoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla, which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli.\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Lovelytheband", "text_new": "{{+r|date=September 2019}}{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Lovelytheband\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Lovelytheband Columbus OH 2018.jpg\n| landscape           = yes\n| caption             = From left to right:  Jordan Greenwald, Mitchy Collins, and Sam Price.\n| origin              = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Indie pop]]|[[indie rock]]|[[alternative rock]]}}\n| years_active        = 2016\u2013present\n| label               = {{hlist|[[Another Century Records|Another Century]]|[[Century Media Records|Century Media]]|[[RED Distribution|RED]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|lovelytheband.com}}\n| current_members     = {{unbulleted list|Mitchy Collins|Jordan Greenwald|Sam Price|}}\n}}\n\n'''Lovelytheband''' (stylized as '''lovelytheband''') is an American [[indie pop]] band that formed in 2016 in [[Los Angeles]]. The band consists of vocalist Mitchy Collins, guitarist Jordan Greenwald, and drummer Sam Price. The band is most known for their single \"[[Broken (Lovelytheband song)|Broken]]\" which charted on several US ''Billboard'' charts.\n\nThe band debuted in April 2017 with their single \"Broken\" which quickly earned over three million streams on [[Spotify]]. The single charted on several ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts. It topped the ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart and ''Billboard'' Rock Airplay chart for several weeks. The single also became the band's first top 10 on the ''Billboard'' Radio Songs chart and first top 40 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\nIn September 2017, the band released their first EP, ''Everything I Could Never Say...''. They released the single \"[[These Are My Friends]]\" in May 2018. On August 3, 2018, they released their debut album ''[[Finding It Hard to Smile]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===2016\u20132018: \"Broken\" and ''Everything I Could Never Say...''===\nMitchy Collins, Jordan Greenwald, and Sam Price met and formed the band while at a nightclub in [[West Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Mitch |last=Mosk |date=April 20, 2017 |url=http://atwoodmagazine.com/broken-lovelytheband-review/ |title=True Connection and Perfect Imperfection in lovelytheband's Debut \"Broken\" |website=Atwood Magazine |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109180910/http://atwoodmagazine.com/broken-lovelytheband-review/ |archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/lovelytheband/1220215284 |title=Apple Music Preview |website=Apple Music |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109181104/https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/lovelytheband/1220215284 |archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=October 5, 2017 |url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/indie-spotlight-lovelytheband |title=Indie Spotlight: lovelytheband |website=BMI |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121952/https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/indie-spotlight-lovelytheband |archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>The band then released their debut single, \"Broken\", in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=Rania |last=Aniftos |date=April 13, 2017 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7759741/lovelytheband-debut-single-broken-premiere |title=lovely.the.band Finds Love That Heals in Debut Single 'Broken': Exclusive Premiere |website=Billboard |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929121457/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7759741/lovelytheband-debut-single-broken-premiere |archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> \n\n\"Broken\" charted on several ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts. It topped the ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart, dated April 21, 2018, and stayed on top for seven consecutive weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8347407/lovelytheband-alternative-songs-chart-number-one|title=Lovelytheband Leaps to No. 1 on Alternative Songs Chart With 'Broken'|last=Rutherford|first=Kevin|accessdate=August 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808011346/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8347407/lovelytheband-alternative-songs-chart-number-one|archive-date=August 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It topped the ''Billboard'' Rock Airplay chart, dated June 9, 2018, and remained on top for nine consecutive weeks.<ref name=airplay>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459907/lovelytheband-broken-rock-airplay-chart|title=Lovelytheband's 'Broken' Rules Rock Airplay Chart|last=Rutherford|first=Kevin|accessdate=August 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807220419/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459907/lovelytheband-broken-rock-airplay-chart|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It peaked at number 10 on the ''Billboard'' Radio Songs chart (airplay chart across all genres), number 14 on the [[Mainstream Top 40]] chart (airplay chart for pop songs),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/radio-songs|title=Radio Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> and number 29 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"Hot 100 Nov 10\"/> The single became the band's first top 10 on the ''Billboard'' Radio Songs chart and first top 40 on the Hot 100. It was also one of the four songs in 2018 that managed to chart in both the Alternative Songs chart and the Top 10 of the Radio Songs chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8482931/lovelytheband-broken-climbs-hot-100-chart-moves|title=Lovelytheband's 'Broken' Continues Alternative's Steady Radio Success and More Hot 100 Chart Moves|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing with [[Another Century Records]], they released their debut EP, ''Everything I Could Never Say...'', in September 2017.<ref name=\"Apple\" /><ref name=\"Genius\">{{cite web |date=September 22, 2017 |url=https://genius.com/albums/Lovelytheband/Everything-i-could-never-say |title=Album ''everything i could never say..'' |website=Genius |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109181149/https://genius.com/albums/Lovelytheband/Everything-i-could-never-say |archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> The band then toured with The Wrecks and La Bouquet.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\n===2018-present: ''Finding It Hard to Smile''===\nOn May 11, 2018, the band released the single \"[[These Are My Friends]]\" from their upcoming debut album. The album, ''[[Finding It Hard to Smile]]'', was then released on August 3, 2018.<ref name=\"AppleAlbum\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/finding-it-hard-to-smile/1396231359|title=\"Finding It Hard to Smile\" by lovelytheband|website=Apple Music|accessdate=July 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724062900/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/finding-it-hard-to-smile/1396231359|archive-date=July 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=abcnradio>{{cite news|title=Lovelytheband Announces Debut Album 'Finding It Hard to Smile'  |url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/6/29/lovelytheband-announces-debut-album-finding-it-hard-to-smile.html |work=[[ABC News Radio]] |date=June 29, 2018 |accessdate=November 27, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227213731/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/6/29/lovelytheband-announces-debut-album-finding-it-hard-to-smile.html |archivedate=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe band went on their first headlining tour, the Broken Like Me Tour, which started on August 15, 2018. The tour visited Canada and the United States. They also toured as the opening act for the European leg of [[5 Seconds of Summer]]'s [[Meet You There Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8472066/lovelytheband-interview-broken-breakthrough-alt-hit|title=How Three Strangers Became Lovelytheband, With 2018's Breakthrough Alt Hit|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref> The band is scheduled to go on their second headlining tour, Finding It Hard to Smile Tour, to support their debut album. The tour will visit cities across the US and Canada, starting March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2019-01-16-lovelytheband-announce-finding-it-hard-to-smile-tour-dates/|title=lovelytheband Announce 'Finding It Hard to Smile' Tour Dates|publisher=iHeartRadio|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Finding It Hard to Smile]]'' (2018)\n\n===Extended plays===\n* ''Everything I Could Never Say...'' (2017)<ref name=\"Genius\" />\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br /><ref name=\"Hot 100 Nov 10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2018-11-10 |title=Hot 100: November 10, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Adult Top 40|US<br />Adult]]<br /><ref name=\"Adult Pop Nov 17\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/adult-pop-songs |title=Adult Pop: November 17, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Alternative Songs|US<br />Alt.]]<br /><ref>Peaks on the Alternative Songs chart:\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/char